We start by looking at the American Airlines Baggage Claim Data¶

Create a monthly index for the series¶

In [ ]:
american_df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(american_df['Date'], format="%b-%y")
american_bag_ts = pd.Series(american_df['Baggage'].values, index=american_df['Date'])
american_bag_ts.index.freq = 'MS'

Plot the American baggage claims series¶

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
american_bag_ts.plot()
plt.title("Baggage Claims for American Airlines")
plt.xlabel("Date")
plt.ylabel("Number of Baggage Claims")
plt.show()

Conduct Ljung Box test on the American Airlines Baggage Claims series using 10 lags to see if the series is white noise¶

In [ ]:
american_bags = american_df[['Baggage']]

sm.stats.acorr_ljungbox(american_bags, lags=[10], return_df=True)
Out[ ]:
lb_stat lb_pvalue
10 345.847732 3.029922e-68

Since the p-value is near zero, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the series is not white noise.¶

Next, we will plot the ACF and PACF for the American Airlines Baggage Claims series¶

In [ ]:
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(12, 12))
plot_acf(american_bag_ts, ax=ax1, zero=False)
plot_pacf(american_bag_ts, ax=ax2, zero=False)
plt.show()

We see that there is seasonality in the data set, so we will take a 12-month seasonal difference.¶

In [ ]:
# Fit ARIMA(0,0,0)x(0,1,0)[12] model to the data - This is simply taking the 12-month seasonal difference

fit_ARD12 = ARIMA(american_bag_ts, order=(0,0,0), seasonal_order=(0, 1, 0, 12)).fit()

# Plot ACF and PACF for residuals from the seasonal difference in order to
# assess the correlation still remaining in the data

residuals12 = fit_ARD12.resid

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(12, 12))
plot_acf(residuals12, ax=ax1, zero=False)
plot_pacf(residuals12, ax=ax2, zero=False, lags=9)
plt.show()

Now, we see that by taking a 12-month seasonal difference, our time series looks like it has an AR signature.¶

We will now fit an ARIMA model to the data:¶

In [ ]:
# Fit ARIMA(1,0,0)x(0,1,1)[12] model to the data

#Best model for Baggage Complaints for American is ARIMA(1,0,0)x(0,1,1)[12]
fit_AR1 = ARIMA(american_bag_ts, order=(1,0,0), seasonal_order=(0, 1, 1, 12)).fit()


# Summary of the ARIMA model
print(fit_AR1.summary())

# Examine residuals from the model
residuals = fit_AR1.resid
plt.plot(residuals)
plt.title('Residuals')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

#Generate the predicted values for the series
pred_units = fit_AR1.get_prediction()
print(pred_units)

Calculate the Forecast Error¶

In [ ]:
# calc error
errors = prediction_df['Baggage'] - prediction_df['predicted_mean']
# absolue value of error
errors_abs = errors.abs()
# -- mape --
mape = (errors_abs/prediction_df['Baggage'].abs()).mean()
# -- rmse
rmse = (errors**2).mean()**0.5
# -- print it out
print(f'MAPE = {mape:.3%}')
print(f'RMSE = {rmse:,.3f}')

MAPE = 14.439%
RMSE = 2,990.367

Our forecast yields a MAPE of 14.439%, which is good considering how noisy this dataset is.¶
